00:37:03.170 --> 00:37:06.020 align:middle line:90%


00:37:06.020 --> 00:37:09.352 align:middle line:84%
The arguments to do
so are convincing.

00:37:09.352 --> 00:37:10.310 align:middle line:90%
>> [NON-ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:37:10.310 --> 00:37:12.440 align:middle line:84%
>> The consumption
of animal products--

00:37:12.440 --> 00:37:14.030 align:middle line:90%
milk and meat and eggs--

00:37:14.030 --> 00:37:17.750 align:middle line:84%
produces more greenhouse
gases than all transport,

00:37:17.750 --> 00:37:21.890 align:middle line:84%
ships, cars,
aeroplanes combined.

00:37:21.890 --> 00:37:25.430 align:middle line:84%
A vegetarian diet can balance
one's own carbon footprint

00:37:25.430 --> 00:37:28.340 align:middle line:90%
by 50%, a vegan diet up to 90%.

00:37:28.340 --> 00:37:31.130 align:middle line:90%


00:37:31.130 --> 00:37:34.130 align:middle line:84%
But what if we could eat
meat whilst also preventing

00:37:34.130 --> 00:37:35.540 align:middle line:90%
animal cruelty?

00:37:35.540 --> 00:37:36.800 align:middle line:90%
Impossible?

00:37:36.800 --> 00:37:39.200 align:middle line:84%
At the University of
Maastricht in Holland,

00:37:39.200 --> 00:37:43.460 align:middle line:84%
Professor Mark Post is working
on a decidedly non-vegan

00:37:43.460 --> 00:37:47.270 align:middle line:84%
alternative to save the
planet and combat hunger--

00:37:47.270 --> 00:37:51.500 align:middle line:84%
artificial meat made
from cows' stem cells.

00:37:51.500 --> 00:37:54.120 align:middle line:84%
>> All of us, but also cows,
have in their muscle stem

00:37:54.120 --> 00:37:54.920 align:middle line:90%
cells.

00:37:54.920 --> 00:37:58.280 align:middle line:10%
They are designated
skeletal muscle stem cells,

00:37:58.280 --> 00:38:00.590 align:middle line:10%
they can only produce
muscle tissue.

00:38:00.590 --> 00:38:03.710 align:middle line:84%
And they're sitting
there doing nothing,

00:38:03.710 --> 00:38:06.810 align:middle line:84%
waiting to repair the
muscle when it's injured.

00:38:06.810 --> 00:38:09.080 align:middle line:90%
That's their role in life.

00:38:09.080 --> 00:38:10.790 align:middle line:84%
They can do that
inside the body,

00:38:10.790 --> 00:38:12.830 align:middle line:84%
but they can also do
that outside of the body.

00:38:12.830 --> 00:38:15.860 align:middle line:90%


00:38:15.860 --> 00:38:18.800 align:middle line:84%
>> Professor Post presented
the fruits of his labors

00:38:18.800 --> 00:38:24.140 align:middle line:90%
to the world press in 2014.

00:38:24.140 --> 00:38:27.130 align:middle line:10%
The first hamburger
grown in the laboratory.

00:38:27.130 --> 00:38:31.880 align:middle line:90%
Cost-- $250,000 for one patty.

00:38:31.880 --> 00:38:33.770 align:middle line:84%
It took the scientists
three months

00:38:33.770 --> 00:38:36.260 align:middle line:84%
to grow the hamburger
from the stem cells,

00:38:36.260 --> 00:38:39.830 align:middle line:84%
quicker than a cow would
ever be able to do it.

00:38:39.830 --> 00:38:42.020 align:middle line:84%
Fundamentally, the
technique could also

00:38:42.020 --> 00:38:43.850 align:middle line:90%
work with chicken and lamb.

00:38:43.850 --> 00:38:45.650 align:middle line:90%
The possibilities are endless.

00:38:45.650 --> 00:38:49.710 align:middle line:90%


00:38:49.710 --> 00:38:54.230 align:middle line:84%
>> So we have been able from
that small sample to culture

00:38:54.230 --> 00:38:57.740 align:middle line:84%
sufficient cells
for that hamburger,

00:38:57.740 --> 00:39:01.190 align:middle line:84%
and if you do the math,
if you calculate--

00:39:01.190 --> 00:39:03.740 align:middle line:84%
and the number of doubling
that you can get out

00:39:03.740 --> 00:39:06.140 align:middle line:84%
of these cells,
that small sample

00:39:06.140 --> 00:39:08.720 align:middle line:84%
could produce 10,000
kilos of meat.

00:39:08.720 --> 00:39:11.670 align:middle line:90%


00:39:11.670 --> 00:39:14.730 align:middle line:84%
>> Two stem cells could
potentially become 10 tons

00:39:14.730 --> 00:39:18.750 align:middle line:84%
of meat, and no cow, sheep,
or chicken would need to die

00:39:18.750 --> 00:39:19.770 align:middle line:90%
for it.

00:39:19.770 --> 00:39:22.020 align:middle line:84%
Will the meat of
tomorrow no longer come

00:39:22.020 --> 00:39:25.650 align:middle line:84%
from the barn or the
field, but the bioreactor?

00:39:25.650 --> 00:39:28.740 align:middle line:84%
What consequences does this
technological breakthrough

00:39:28.740 --> 00:39:30.630 align:middle line:90%
have for the environment?

00:39:30.630 --> 00:39:35.430 align:middle line:84%
>> We have 1 and 1/2
billion cows on this planet.

00:39:35.430 --> 00:39:38.430 align:middle line:84%
And this technology still
would require some cows,

00:39:38.430 --> 00:39:41.590 align:middle line:84%
because they need to
donate those stem cells.

00:39:41.590 --> 00:39:45.020 align:middle line:84%
But you could go down from 1
and 1/2 billion to, say, 30,000,

00:39:45.020 --> 00:39:48.990 align:middle line:90%
35,000 across the world.

00:39:48.990 --> 00:39:52.140 align:middle line:84%
>> Could Mark Post's
visions become a reality?

00:39:52.140 --> 00:39:54.600 align:middle line:84%
Can the greenhouse gases
caused by mass farming

00:39:54.600 --> 00:39:56.670 align:middle line:90%
be drastically reduced?

00:39:56.670 --> 00:39:59.250 align:middle line:84%
Artificial meat from
bioreactors-- ethical,

00:39:59.250 --> 00:40:01.380 align:middle line:90%
efficient, and ecological.

00:40:01.380 --> 00:40:04.950 align:middle line:84%
Could eating meat be a way to
prevent animal cruelty and save

00:40:04.950 --> 00:40:06.150 align:middle line:90%
the planet?

00:40:06.150 --> 00:40:09.472 align:middle line:84%
Only if it tastes
good and comes cheap.

00:40:09.472 --> 00:40:11.430 align:middle line:84%
>> With the current
technology, if we scale up,

00:40:11.430 --> 00:40:14.440 align:middle line:84%
the cost would be
about $65 per kilo--

00:40:14.440 --> 00:40:16.960 align:middle line:90%
so about 50 euro per kilo.

00:40:16.960 --> 00:40:20.005 align:middle line:84%
Which is still expensive, it's
still 30 times more expensive

00:40:20.005 --> 00:40:21.630 align:middle line:84%
than what we have
right now, but that's

00:40:21.630 --> 00:40:23.422 align:middle line:84%
with the current
technology, and we already

00:40:23.422 --> 00:40:29.090 align:middle line:84%
know which innovations
we need to--

00:40:29.090 --> 00:40:33.000 align:middle line:84%
we are looking for to
get that price down.

00:40:33.000 --> 00:40:35.950 align:middle line:84%
>> The consumption of animal
products such as meat, milk,

00:40:35.950 --> 00:40:40.050 align:middle line:84%
and eggs creates more greenhouse
gases than all transport--

00:40:40.050 --> 00:40:43.080 align:middle line:84%
ships, cars, and
aeroplanes combined.

00:40:43.080 --> 00:40:45.210 align:middle line:84%
And some people are
already dreaming

00:40:45.210 --> 00:40:48.150 align:middle line:84%
of making milk and
cheese in bioreactors.

00:40:48.150 --> 00:40:49.900 align:middle line:90%
No animals needed at all.

00:40:49.900 --> 00:40:55.110 align:middle line:90%


00:40:55.110 --> 00:40:58.770 align:middle line:84%
>> I think it's actually a great
idea to make the milk proteins

00:40:58.770 --> 00:41:03.890 align:middle line:84%
by bacteria or yeast or
whatever organism it is--

00:41:03.890 --> 00:41:06.030 align:middle line:90%
is used to produce that.

00:41:06.030 --> 00:41:09.360 align:middle line:84%
And add water and other
substances and fat, maybe,

00:41:09.360 --> 00:41:12.880 align:middle line:90%
to create the same product.

00:41:12.880 --> 00:41:17.280 align:middle line:84%
I think that's a great idea,
because milk is a problematic--

00:41:17.280 --> 00:41:22.856 align:middle line:84%
probably as problematic as meat
is a problematic commodity.

00:41:22.856 --> 00:41:28.100 align:middle line:90%


00:41:28.100 --> 00:41:30.830 align:middle line:84%
>> The Bay Area around
San Francisco is one

00:41:30.830 --> 00:41:33.530 align:middle line:84%
of the world's
hotbeds of innovation.

00:41:33.530 --> 00:41:36.560 align:middle line:84%
This is where the computer
revolution of the 20th century

00:41:36.560 --> 00:41:37.730 align:middle line:90%
took place--

00:41:37.730 --> 00:41:41.450 align:middle line:90%
Apple, Intel, Google, and Coke.

00:41:41.450 --> 00:41:44.420 align:middle line:84%
In the 21st century,
the biotech revolution

00:41:44.420 --> 00:41:47.510 align:middle line:84%
is to follow the digital
one, and once again, it all

00:41:47.510 --> 00:41:50.210 align:middle line:90%
starts in an old garage.

00:41:50.210 --> 00:41:52.550 align:middle line:84%
Near Berkeley
University, biohackers

00:41:52.550 --> 00:41:56.630 align:middle line:84%
come together to make vegan
cheese out of marine mammals.

00:41:56.630 --> 00:41:58.850 align:middle line:84%
What may seem impossible
at first glance

00:41:58.850 --> 00:42:03.200 align:middle line:84%
could become a reality when
you take a closer look.

00:42:03.200 --> 00:42:05.450 align:middle line:10%
>> The narwhal is just
because it's kind of cold--

00:42:05.450 --> 00:42:06.830 align:middle line:10%
because we can do it.

00:42:06.830 --> 00:42:12.110 align:middle line:10%
We can do any mammal that
has had its genome sequenced.

00:42:12.110 --> 00:42:13.800 align:middle line:84%
And so this was
really sort of to get

00:42:13.800 --> 00:42:15.050 align:middle line:90%
people excited about the idea.

00:42:15.050 --> 00:42:17.500 align:middle line:84%
Hey, we can do something
really different because--

00:42:17.500 --> 00:42:20.000 align:middle line:84%
yeah, it's probably very
hard to milk a narwhal.

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:22.970 align:middle line:84%
I don't think anybody's ever
made narwhal cheese before.

00:42:22.970 --> 00:42:24.650 align:middle line:84%
So this is showing
that not only can we

00:42:24.650 --> 00:42:27.830 align:middle line:84%
reproduce things that
already exist in the world--

00:42:27.830 --> 00:42:30.500 align:middle line:84%
cow milk cheese, we can
do some really new things

00:42:30.500 --> 00:42:32.158 align:middle line:84%
that are really only
possible this way.

00:42:32.158 --> 00:42:33.950 align:middle line:10%
>> Basically this is
pretty much like the--

00:42:33.950 --> 00:42:36.380 align:middle line:10%
>> Modern gene technology
makes it possible,

00:42:36.380 --> 00:42:37.750 align:middle line:10%
as does the internet.

00:42:37.750 --> 00:42:40.850 align:middle line:10%
One can buy genetic mammal
material, exactly the part

00:42:40.850 --> 00:42:43.340 align:middle line:10%
the cow's the milk
proteins, proteins

00:42:43.340 --> 00:42:48.740 align:middle line:10%
that can be mass-reproduced
within bacteria or yeast cells.

00:42:48.740 --> 00:42:51.950 align:middle line:84%
>> It's pretty easy to order the
plasmid complete with your gene

00:42:51.950 --> 00:42:52.848 align:middle line:90%
of interest in it.

00:42:52.848 --> 00:42:54.140 align:middle line:90%
So that's what we've done here.

00:42:54.140 --> 00:42:56.750 align:middle line:84%
So it's got that gene
that tells the yeast how

00:42:56.750 --> 00:42:59.110 align:middle line:84%
to make this particular
protein, and it's

00:42:59.110 --> 00:43:00.710 align:middle line:90%
got a few other features, too.

00:43:00.710 --> 00:43:03.260 align:middle line:84%
It actually tells the yeast once
that protein's made, kick it

00:43:03.260 --> 00:43:04.690 align:middle line:90%
out of the yeast cell.

00:43:04.690 --> 00:43:08.490 align:middle line:84%
That makes it easier
to purify afterwards.

00:43:08.490 --> 00:43:11.820 align:middle line:84%
>> At no stage in the process
is an animal involved.

00:43:11.820 --> 00:43:15.160 align:middle line:84%
Theoretically, it should be
possible to genetically create

00:43:15.160 --> 00:43:18.030 align:middle line:84%
vegan milk proteins
in yeast cells,

00:43:18.030 --> 00:43:20.620 align:middle line:84%
just as insulin is being
produced in yeast cells

00:43:20.620 --> 00:43:21.420 align:middle line:90%
already.

00:43:21.420 --> 00:43:24.280 align:middle line:90%


00:43:24.280 --> 00:43:28.450 align:middle line:84%
Today, the biohackers from the
Counter Culture Lab in Berkeley

00:43:28.450 --> 00:43:32.770 align:middle line:84%
are locking a human breast
milk protein into a yeast cell.

00:43:32.770 --> 00:43:36.190 align:middle line:84%
It would be the first component
of artificial human breast

00:43:36.190 --> 00:43:39.850 align:middle line:84%
milk that together with
plants, oil, sugar, and water,

00:43:39.850 --> 00:43:43.290 align:middle line:84%
could form the basis
for a vegan cheese.

00:43:43.290 --> 00:43:47.820 align:middle line:90%
>> 5, 4, 3, 2, 1.

00:43:47.820 --> 00:43:52.200 align:middle line:90%


00:43:52.200 --> 00:43:53.120 align:middle line:90%
>> That's it, right?

00:43:53.120 --> 00:43:53.430 align:middle line:90%
>> Yes!

00:43:53.430 --> 00:43:54.638 align:middle line:90%
>> 4.9, almost exactly right.

00:43:54.638 --> 00:43:55.448 align:middle line:90%
Good time.

00:43:55.448 --> 00:43:56.780 align:middle line:90%
>> Awesome!

00:43:56.780 --> 00:43:56.900 align:middle line:90%
Ah!

00:43:56.900 --> 00:43:57.700 align:middle line:90%
>> OK.

00:43:57.700 --> 00:43:58.630 align:middle line:90%
>> Phew!

00:43:58.630 --> 00:43:59.880 align:middle line:90%
>> OK, so now we pull it out--

00:43:59.880 --> 00:44:01.128 align:middle line:90%
>> And I'm still alive.

00:44:01.128 --> 00:44:01.928 align:middle line:90%
[LAUGHS]

00:44:01.928 --> 00:44:05.750 align:middle line:10%
>> The theoretical path to
making vegan cheese is known.

00:44:05.750 --> 00:44:08.570 align:middle line:84%
The practical implementation
with donated equipment

00:44:08.570 --> 00:44:12.950 align:middle line:84%
from the biotech industry
seems controllable, possible.

00:44:12.950 --> 00:44:15.380 align:middle line:10%
Even the implementation
of a protocol

00:44:15.380 --> 00:44:19.100 align:middle line:10%
by a colorful mix of academic
amateurs, biocomputer

00:44:19.100 --> 00:44:23.290 align:middle line:10%
scientists geologists, software
engineers, and chemists

00:44:23.290 --> 00:44:24.680 align:middle line:10%
is possible.

00:44:24.680 --> 00:44:27.770 align:middle line:84%
Yet, milk proteins
are very complex.

00:44:27.770 --> 00:44:31.380 align:middle line:84%
If it were that simple, we
would already have vegan cheese.

00:44:31.380 --> 00:44:34.560 align:middle line:84%
A long and rocky
road lies ahead.

00:44:34.560 --> 00:44:35.810 align:middle line:90%
>> The real challenge is this.

00:44:35.810 --> 00:44:37.803 align:middle line:84%
It will be isolating
the proteins,

00:44:37.803 --> 00:44:40.220 align:middle line:84%
getting them really pure after
they come out of the yeast,

00:44:40.220 --> 00:44:43.880 align:middle line:84%
because of course the yeast is
making other protein as well.

00:44:43.880 --> 00:44:46.280 align:middle line:84%
And then reconstructing
these several proteins

00:44:46.280 --> 00:44:48.950 align:middle line:84%
to make the larger
protein structure.

00:44:48.950 --> 00:44:52.130 align:middle line:84%
And this has been done
in the literature when

00:44:52.130 --> 00:44:55.580 align:middle line:84%
these proteins have been
isolated individually

00:44:55.580 --> 00:45:00.950 align:middle line:84%
from the mammalian sources, but
we've never done it from yeast.

00:45:00.950 --> 00:45:03.590 align:middle line:84%
And if we get everything
exactly right,

00:45:03.590 --> 00:45:06.050 align:middle line:84%
it will work the same way,
but if anything's a little bit

00:45:06.050 --> 00:45:07.883 align:middle line:84%
different, we may have
to do some extra work

00:45:07.883 --> 00:45:11.420 align:middle line:90%
to reconstruct those micelles.

00:45:11.420 --> 00:45:14.990 align:middle line:84%
>> The relevant American
supervising body, the FDA,

00:45:14.990 --> 00:45:18.140 align:middle line:84%
has no concerns
regarding vegan cheese,

00:45:18.140 --> 00:45:22.160 align:middle line:84%
but cheese from human breast
milk meets resistance.

00:45:22.160 --> 00:45:26.960 align:middle line:84%
These are cultural reservations
that weigh heavily on this.

